T1  - Fiscal policy and foreign debt
AU  - Borensztein, Eduardo R.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
SP  - 53
EP  - 75
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90038-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219968990038X
AB  - This paper shows that an expansionary fiscal policy may have the consequence of either increasing or decreasing the level of foreign debt in the context of a two-sector small economy that produces traded and nontraded goods. The long-run effect of a fiscal expansion depends on a measure of the relative capital intensity of the two productive sectors, in addition to the composition of private and public spending. The short-run effect of a transitory fiscal expansion is critically influenced by the extent to which investment reacts to current and prospective profits.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On occasional monetary policy coordinations that fix the exchange rate
AU  - Lewis, Karen K.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
SP  - 139
EP  - 155
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90042-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900421
AB  - Occasionally, central banks have simultaneously expanded monetary policy to prevent adverse effects upon the exchange rate. This paper offers a motivation for this behavior. Although governments prefer non-cooperative policies most of the time, upon viewing sufficiently excessive disturbances to output, the benefits of stabilization become greater than the costs required to institute temporary policy coordinations. Thus, coordination occurs during periods when the gains are the greatest. Also, since the authorities target a higher employment level than labor markets, coordination of policies occurs with greater frequency during periods of low rather than high output shocks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Inside money and the open economy
AU  - Freeman, Scott
AU  - Murphy, Robert G.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
SP  - 29
EP  - 51
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90037-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900378
AB  - This paper presents a theoretical model of a world economy with international capital mobility, non-substitutable national currencies, and flexible exchange rates. An essential feature of the model is that individuals face a non-trivial choice between real assets intermediated through banks (inside money) and unbacked currency (outside money). Real shocks affect the relative demand for inside as opposed to outside money (the money multiplier) and are transmitted internationally through capital markets, thereby affecting money stocks, price levels, and output abroad. The analysis provides a possible explanation for the pattern of comovements in money supplies, inflation rates, and output levels across countries.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal trade taxes for a large country with non-atomistic firms
AU  - Rodrik, Dani
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
SP  - 157
EP  - 167
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90043-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900433
AB  - The conventional prescription for a country possessing market power in world markets is an import tariff or export tax. Typically, a country will have a continuum of traders, differentiated both by size and behavior. Optimal policy then involves a structure of trade taxes, rather than a uniform tax or tariff, with larger firms generally taxed at lower rates than smaller ones. When policy is constrained to a uniform tax, optimal policy depends both on the foreign demand (or supply) elasticity and the size distribution of firms. The principles derived here are applied numerically to Indonesia's exports of nutmeg.
ER  - 

